The Balkan 16th-19th century concept of "haiduts"/"hajduks" is basically the middleground because they were functionally just forest bandits robbing random people but it eventually flowed into them being seen/becoming anti-Ottoman political revolutionaries

If you read Bram Stoker in Dracula he originally uses the term "Austrian yoke" in the same way revolutionaries talk about "the Ottoman yoke" in Bulgaria. Vasil Levski's letters are very good and Che Guevara read them too. It's very easy to get a "feel" for the time from old texts

I think Garibaldi's unification is the key element because a lot of hajduks seem to have been involved in his forces, it really flows very easily imo especially if you remember how Soviets would just set apolitical prisoners free and put them in charge if a town had no communists
